tweet: We are confident that the cost to mint multiple Azukis will be lower than anything we've seen in the space. All projects should strive to minimize the gas burden for their community as much as they can.   @AzukiZen is minting on January 12 @ 10am PST. IKZ!

name: AZUKI
tweet: These three optimizations are how ERC721A is able to achieve minting multiple NFTs for nearly the same gas as minting just one. You can find a more detailed dive into the technicals here:  https://t.co/GbKSmmJxoW

name: AZUKI
tweet: The key here is if we need to determine the owner of a specific tokenId, we don't need an address explicitly set for that slot. The ownerOf function is changed to do the following:  https://t.co/BbJm7k66FD

name: AZUKI
tweet: ERC721A saves the owner value only *once* per mint txn, without any data loss. This is possible because ERC721A assumes that token ids are minted sequentially starting from 0.  https://t.co/Of9vuNSs1x

name: AZUKI
tweet: Optimization 3: updating owner data once üîß  This piece has never been seen before in the space. Currently, all contracts explicitly set ownership on every individual token mint. Minting 5 NFTs in a txn means 5 owner writes, with each storage write costing ~20k gas.

name: AZUKI
tweet: Optimization 2: updating owner balance once üîß  @OpenZeppelin's ERC721 does not include a batch mint API. The vast majority of the NFT space uses _safeMint in a loop for multiple mints. Our batch mint API updates the balance count in one storage operation instead of repeatedly.

name: AZUKI
tweet: Optimization 1: removing duplicate storage from OpenZeppelin‚Äôs ERC721Enumerable üîß  ERC721A assumes tokens are minted serially starting from 0, which lets us remove some storage. We also optimize for writes over reads in order to lower cost.

name: AZUKI
tweet: So how does it work? We made three key optimizations that reduce gas while still maintaining feature parity with ERC721Enumerable. We chose not to cut IERC721Enumerable because we believe the API will prove valuable as web3 grows.

name: AZUKI
tweet: It's impossible to predict the gas price and ETH price at time of mint, but if we assume 300 gwei and $3500/ETH, these are the projected dollar savings for the community. Minting five NFTs is essentially the same price as minting one.  https://t.co/u4YVXvXMLX

name: AZUKI
tweet: But first, a look at the savings. We have measured the gas required to mint using @OpenZeppelin's ERC721Enumerable vs ERC721A. The only difference between these two columns is which _safeMint implementation is being used.  https://t.co/sreiLWP8Us

name: AZUKI
tweet: Gas prices on Ethereum have been high for months, prompting dev teams to adapt. When minting multiple tokens, the gas cost required is proportional to the quantity of tokens being minted. ERC721A has three key optimizations that greatly reduce the additional gas required.  https://t.co/MVVNujEppo
